        {
            "Id": "StatueSekhmet",
            "IsStatic": "True",
            "Location": [
                1.42,
                7.5,
                -15.6
            ],
            "Description": "Statue of the Goddess Sekhmet",
            "Model": "sekhmet_granite2",
            "ExtendedDescription": "New Kingdom, Dyn. XVIII, reign of Amenhotep III\nBlack granite\nFrom the temple of Ptah, Karnak.\n\nThe quick-tempered goddess Sekhmet personified the destructive power of the sun. However, once ritually appeased, the ‘furious one who kills’ became the ‘satisfied one who gives life’. Once assuaged, she became a beneficent and protective entity who granted the king long years of renewed life and a prosperous reign, as well as protection against illness and enemies. \n\nHolding life and death in her hands, she had the privilege of preserving life, as well as the power of sending calamities. The suffocating heat of the month of Epiphi (May-June), fevers, epidemics and the pollution of the waters of the Nile were considered to be acts of the goddess Sekhmet and her emissaries that preceded the annual arrival of the flood. \n\nAll were vulnerable to her seven arrows, especially during the epagomenal days (additional days of the year). Even the spoiling of food was attributed to her short-tempered actions. The wab-priest was able to interact with this deity and assuage her as his purity immunized him from the dangerous effects of her power.\n\nKing Amenhotep III commissioned hundreds of statues of the goddess for his temple of millions of years in western Thebes, the Amenophium. These statues were meant as a monumental prayer to appease the goddess —perhaps in a time of of epidemic—and thus guarantee peace and health.",
            "Scale": [
                0.003,
                0.003,
                0.003
            ],
            "Rotation": [
                -180.0,
