    "Characters": [
        {
            "Id": "Priest",
            "Name": "Yuny",
            "Description": "The <i>wab</i>-priest Yuny",
            "ExtendedDescription": "New Kingdom, Dyn. XIX, reign of Sethy.\n\nYuny was a pure (<i>wab</i>) priest of the goddess Sekhmet, a type of ancient Egyptian ritualist closely linked to the Houses of Life that played an important role in the protection of the country, the living image of Apis and the practice of medicine. <i>Wab</i>-priests are documented in the Edwin Smith and Ebers medical papyruses as specialists in the diagnosis of illnesses. They were experts in the art of diagnosing illnesses by touching their patients. Thanks to their medical knowledge, <i>wab</i>-priests were also required to accompany members of mining and trading expeditions. \n\nThe pure priests (<i>wab</i>) of the goddess Sekhmet appear to have frequently fulfilled additional liturgical functions as lector priests within temple contexts, as evidenced by an inscription on the statue of Yuny and his wife Renenutet, discovered in the tomb chapel of Amenhotep at Asyut (MMA 15.2.1).The list of all his titles on the base of the statue tells us that Yuny was a priest-reader, head of the pure priests of Sekhmet and son of Amenhotep, who held the same post.\n\nThanks to their purity, Yuny was able to assuage Sekhmet while being protected from the dangerous effects of the goddess’ power. However, the duality of Sekhmet –the furious one who kills/the satisfied one who vitalises– also characterised the priests who officiated at her worship. \n\nThe spells and acts of Sekhmet’s wab-priest could be considered the causes of disease and illness. This is due to the fact that once the goddess had been appeased and neutralised, Sekhmet’s attributes were transferred to and assimilated by her officiant. The survival of these officiants into the Roman period is further proof of the cultural resilience of ancient Egyptian traditions under Greco-Roman domination.",
            "Model": "Mago-03",
            "Scale": [
                3.0,
                3.0,
                3.0
            ]
        },
